Introduction:¶

Video games have been a popular and rising medium of entertainment over the past few decades. With the vast array of genres, platforms, and publishers over the years, the task of choosing which game is worth investing time and money in can be daunting. This is where our project steps in. Our objective is to examine a comprehensive dataset of video game sales up until 2016 to better predict and personalize game recommendations for individuals. This analysis aims to utilize a cluster algorithm to identify patterns and trends in video game preferences and sales that can play a factor in personalized recommendations.

As people who buy and play a lot of video games themselves, we were motivated to take up this endeavor after taking into consideration how many games have been rising in price and oversaturating the market, along with our limited amount of free time thanks to school and work. We found that it would be best if there were some means of personalized recommendations of video games that would save our wallets and make it worth while to put our precious time into.

This analysis is crucial because it supports the creation of a model that not only enhances user engagement by providing gamers with recommendations finely tuned to their tastes, but it also plays a role in helping game developers and marketers to understand their audience better. By predicting and personalizing game recommendations, we can potentially increase user satisfaction and retention rates for video games. Moreover, this project contributes to the idea of an automated recommendation systems based on algorithms and data, which are pivotal in the modern era of digital commerce and online entertainment

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Hypothesis Testing 1: Chi-squared test¶

  • In this analysis, we compared the genre to the sales in each region and globally, aiming to investigate if there is an association between the genre of game and the sales in each respective region.

  • Since we are examining the relationship between two categorical variablesthe genre of games and their overall sales in each regiona chi-squared test is suitable in this case. In a contingency table, the chi-squared test for independence determines if these variables significantly correlate with one another.

Hypothesis: There is an association between users' preferred game genres and their regional sales preferences.

Null Hypothesis: There is no association between users' preferred game genres and their regional sales preferences.

In [275]:
# Create contingency tables for each pair of variables
contingency_na = pd.crosstab(vgs_df['Genre'], vgs_df['NA_Sales'])
contingency_eu = pd.crosstab(vgs_df['Genre'], vgs_df['EU_Sales'])
contingency_jp = pd.crosstab(vgs_df['Genre'], vgs_df['JP_Sales'])
contingency_global = pd.crosstab(vgs_df['Genre'], vgs_df['Global_Sales'])

# Perform chi-squared tests for each contingency table
chi2_na, p_value_na, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_na)
chi2_eu, p_value_eu, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_eu)
chi2_jp, p_value_jp, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_jp)
chi2_global, p_value_global, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_global)

# Print the results of each chi-squared test
print("Chi-squared test statistic and p-value for North America sales:")

print("P-value:", p_value_na)

print("\nChi-squared test statistic and p-value for Europe sales:")

print("P-value:", p_value_eu)

print("\nChi-squared test statistic and p-value for Japan sales:")
print("Chi-squared:", chi2_jp)
print("P-value:", p_value_jp)

print("\nChi-squared test statistic and p-value for global sales:")
print("Chi-squared:", chi2_global)
print("P-value:", p_value_global)

Conclusion 1:¶

North America Sales:

  • P-value: 8.00 x 10^-65

  • Conclusion: Since the p-value is much smaller than our significance level of 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. This meas that there is a statistically significant evidence determining the association between users preferred game genres and their sales preferences in North America.

Europe Sales:

  • P-value: 1.49 x 10^-38

  • Conclusion: Similar to North America, the p-value is much smaller than the our significance level of 0.05. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis. There is statistically significant association between users preferred game genres and their sales preferences in Europe.

Japan Sales:

  • P-value: 4.33 x 10^-180

  • Conclusion: The same rule applies for Japan. The p-value is smaller the the significance level of 0.05 which means that we reject the null hypothesis meaning there is statisically significant evidence portraying the association between users preferred game genres and their sales preferences in Japan.

Global Sales:

  • P-value: 1.22 x 10^-13

  • Conclusion: The p-value is smaller than our significance level 0.05. Therefore, we reject the null hypothesis meaning there is a statistically significant association between users preferred game genres and their sales preferences on a global scale.

Hypothesis Testing 2: Z-Test¶

The general question about developing a recommendation system based on user preferences and sales data is greatly helped by using the z-test to compare the mean total global sales between platforms, such as the PlayStation 2 (PS2) and other popular platforms. This statistical method makes it possible to compare sales performance between various platforms, giving important information about which platforms are more well-liked or profitable in the marketplace. The relative performance of each platform can be determined by applying the z-test to sales data analysis. This information is essential for customizing the recommendation system to users preferred platforms. The z-test also aids in determining whether observed variations in sales performance between platforms are statistically significant, which helps in determining which platforms should be given priority in the recommendation system. Overall, the z-test serves as a complex analytical tool for evaluating platform preferences and informing the design of an effective recommendation system that aligns with user's preferences and sales data.

Hypothesis: The average total game sales of game for the PlayStation 2 are different from the average total game sales for the top 5 platforms compared to the PlayStation 2

Null Hypothesis: There is no significant difference in the average total global sales of games for the PlayStation 2 compared to the top 5 platforms compared to the PlayStation 2

In [277]:
platform_sales = {}
for platform in vgs_df['Platform'].unique():
    platform_sales[platform] = vgs_df[vgs_df['Platform'] == platform]['Global_Sales']

# Get the top 5 platforms
top_platforms = vgs_df['Platform'].value_counts().nlargest(6)[1:].index.tolist()
reference_platform = 'PlayStation 2'

#Perform Z-test for top 5 platforms compared to PS2
def z_test(sample1, sample2):
    n1, n2 = len(sample1), len(sample2)
    mean1, mean2 = sample1.mean(), sample2.mean()
    var1, var2 = sample1.var(), sample2.var()

    pooled_var = ((n1 - 1) * var1 + (n2 - 1) * var2) / (n1 + n2 - 2)
    z_score = (mean1 - mean2) / (pooled_var * ((1/n1) + (1/n2)))**0.5

    p_value = stats.norm.sf(abs(z_score)) * 2  # two-tailed test

    return z_score, p_value

# Compare the top 5 platforms to PS2
for platform in top_platforms:
    if platform == reference_platform:
        continue

    ps2_sales = platform_sales[reference_platform]
    platform_sales_comp = platform_sales[platform]
    z_score, p_value = z_test(ps2_sales, platform_sales_comp)
    print(f"Z-test for {platform} compared to {reference_platform}:")
    print(f"Z-score: {z_score}")
    print(f"P-value: {p_value}\n")

Hypothesis Testing 3: ANOVA Test¶

A solid method for addressing the main issue of building a recommendation system based on user preferences and sales data is provided by the suggested ANOVA test. This analysis offers good insights into how various age demographics affect sales performance by analyzing the relationship between age rating categories and average total global sales of games. The validity of conclusions is ensured by the ANOVA test, which employs statistical rigor to ascertain whether observed differences in sales across age rating categories are statistically significant. Sales data about user age preferences can be used to customize the recommendation system so that games that appeal to particular age groups are recommended, increasing user satisfaction and engagement. As a result, the ANOVA test is a useful tool for creating recommendation systems that successfully incorporate user preferences and sales data, optimizing the gaming experience for diverse demographics.

Hypothesis: There is significant difference in the average global sales of games across different rating categories.

Null Hypothesis: There is no significant difference in the average global sales of games across different rating categories.

In [279]:
#Drop NaN values in 'Rating' and 'Global_Sales' columns
vgs_df.dropna(subset=['Rating', 'Global_Sales'], inplace=True)

rating_sales = {}
for rating in vgs_df['Rating'].unique():
    sales = vgs_df[vgs_df['Rating'] == rating]['Global_Sales']
    if len(sales) >= 2:
        rating_sales[rating] = sales

#Perform ANOVA test for multiple samples
f_statistic, p_value = f_oneway(*rating_sales.values())

print("F-statistic:", f_statistic)
print("P-value:", p_value)

F-statistic: 14.700126996449237
P-value: 8.551358958846202e-17

Conclusion 3:¶

Strong evidence is found in the investigation about the correlation between video game sales worldwide and age rating categories. The computed F-statistic of 14.70 indicates a significant difference in the mean global sales average across different age rating groups. This statistic highlights the significant differences in sales performance between different age groups by evaluating the ratio of variance found between groups to that within groups. Moreover, the remarkably low p-value of roughly 8.55e-17 emphasizes how solid these results are.

This likelihood provides strong evidence against the idea that these disparities happened at random by showing how unlikely it is to observe such large variances in global sales among age rating groups if the null hypothesis were true. Age rating has a substantial impact on video game sales, as the data clearly indicates that the observed disparities in global sales across various age rating groups are statistically significant and unlikely to be the result of chance.

Primary Analysis¶

Now that we have collected, cleaned, and explored our data, it's time to apply machine learning to the idea of predicting personalized game recommendations. The concept of machine learning is an algorithms that becomes better at performing tasks by being given data, effectively 'learning' through experience, and so, we will use a cluster algorithm to perform this analysis and predict these recommendations by giving us a varied clustered of options at the end.

In [281]:
# Select relevant features for clustering
features = ['Genre', 'Platform', 'Publisher']

X = vgs_df[features]

# Perform one-hot encoding
encoder = OneHotEncoder()
X_encoded = encoder.fit_transform(X)

# Apply K-means clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=5, random_state=42)
kmeans.fit(X_encoded)

cluster_labels = kmeans.labels_

# Assign cluster labels to the DataFrame
vgs_df['Cluster'] = cluster_labels

recommendations = []
for cluster in range(5):
    # Find games belonging to the cluster
    cluster_games = vgs_df[vgs_df['Cluster'] == cluster]
    if len(cluster_games) > 0:
        cluster_recommendations = cluster_games.sample(n=5, random_state=42)
        recommendations.append(cluster_recommendations)
    else:
        print(f"No games found in Cluster {cluster+1}")

# Display recommendations
for idx, cluster_recommendations in enumerate(recommendations):
    print(f"Cluster {idx+1} Recommendations:")
    print(cluster_recommendations[['Name', 'Genre', 'Platform', 'Publisher']])
    print()

Visualization¶

After training our model in the previous section with the cluster algorithm, we will now utilize a PCA Cluster Graph to display our analysis.

Principal Component 1 (PC1): This axis shows which direction in the initial feature space there is the most variation in the data. Of all the linear combinations of the original attributes that are feasible, it captures the most variance in the data.

Principal Component 2 (PC2): This axis shows the direction in the original feature space that is orthogonal to PC1 (i.e., perpendicular to PC1) and captures the second most variance in the data.

Every point in the scatter plot represents a data point projected onto the two-dimensional PCA space, in this case, a preference for a certain game. Each point's location along PC1 and PC2 indicates how similar or different it is from other data points in the dataset.

In [282]:
# Apply PCA to reduce data to 2 dimensions
pca = PCA(n_components=2)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_encoded.toarray())

# Plot the clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for cluster in range(5):
    cluster_points = X_pca[cluster_labels == cluster]
    plt.scatter(cluster_points[:, 0], cluster_points[:, 1], label=f'Cluster {cluster+1}')

plt.title('Clusters of Game Preferences')
plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1')
plt.ylabel('Principal Component 2')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Using characteristics like Publisher, Platform, and Genre, the given code uses K-means clustering on the dataset to find groups of similar game tastes. Users are then given game recommendations based on each of the identified clusters.

Games in Cluster 1 include "Dragon Ball Z: Battle of Z" (Fighting), "Petz: Dogz Family" (Simulation), and "Onimusha 2: Samurai's Destiny" (Adventure), demonstrating a wide variety of genres available on various platforms and publishers.

Action games dominate Cluster 2, with titles like "Hunter: The Reckoning Redeemer" and "SpongeBob SquarePants featuring Nicktoons: Glo..." indicating a strong platform preference for action games.

Games in the shooter genre, such as "Singularity" and "Delta Force: Black Hawk Down," are included in Cluster 3, which suggests a predilection for these kinds of games on platforms.

Racing games, such as "Drome Racers" and "The Dukes of Hazzard II: Daisy Dukes It Out," make up the majority of Cluster 4, which suggests a concentrated interest in racing games on many platforms.

Cluster 5 includes games with a sports theme, such as "Major League Baseball 2K9" and "Cabela's Dangerous Hunts 2," suggesting that people favor sports-themed games on platforms like Xbox and PlayStation.

Notice how the clusters are similar in size this could point to a number of underlying variables affecting the clustering outcomes. First of all, it implies that there can be some uniformity in the game sector, with consumers having comparable tastes across all niches. This may be explained by the fact that some game genres, platforms, or publishers are very popular with players, creating groups that are similar to one another. The low variety in the clustering features (publisher, genre, and platform) may also be a factor in the shape similarity of the clusters. When the majority of the games in the dataset have similar attributes, it can make it more difficult to form unique clusters with notably different properties. In addition, the sensitivity of the selected clustering algorithm and the availability and quality of the data used for clustering can have an additional impact on the clustering outcomes.

All things considered, the clustering algorithm is effective in identifying discrete gaming segments with different preferences, offering insights into the heterogeneous gaming market environment. To effectively cater to particular user interests, these clusters might inform marketing campaigns that are specifically targeted as well as game development efforts.

Additionally, cluster 5 was also more noticeable due to its higher placement, which could suggests that games in this area had more success abroad. But cluster 2 stood out as distinct from the others, emphasizing different customer preferences. These results serves to highlight the diverse range of user tastes and habits, along with the many niches in the gaming industry.
